<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="146" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,361,1720]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,297,361,387]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Description.</emphasis>
Body narrowly elongate. Head short with obliquely inclined mouthparts, broadest at across the eyes; frons steep and narrow, with a vague median ridge reaching vertex; genae very short; postvertex of male protruding backward to form a short horn in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[673,754,434,460]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1788,1812]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,1140,1752]" captionTargetId="figure-44@4.[151,1436,1128,1764]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8–13. Head and pronotum of Unicornileptura spp. 8–11, U. emeiensis sp. nov.; 12,13, U. laticollis sp. nov. 8, 9, head in lateral view (a) and frontal view (b); 10–13, pronotum in dorsal view. 8, 10, 12, male; 9, 11, 13, female." pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Fig. 8a</figureCitation>
), triangular shaped in frontal view (
<figureCitation box="[1155,1237,434,461]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1788,1812]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,1140,1752]" captionTargetId="figure-44@4.[151,1436,1128,1764]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8–13. Head and pronotum of Unicornileptura spp. 8–11, U. emeiensis sp. nov.; 12,13, U. laticollis sp. nov. 8, 9, head in lateral view (a) and frontal view (b); 10–13, pronotum in dorsal view. 8, 10, 12, male; 9, 11, 13, female." pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Fig. 8b</figureCitation>
), almost reaching anterior margin of pronotum; temples moderately developed, shorter than longitudinal eye diameter, roundly constricted to neck. Eyes almost entire, finely facetted; interocular space wider than distance between antennal cavities. Maxillary palpus with fusiform terminal segment, about 1.5 times as long as the penultimate segment. Antennae inserted near anterior margin of eyes, reaching or exceeding elytral midlength; scape clavate, abruptly bent down near apex; flagellum filiform with apices of basal 5 flagellomeres slightly thickened, first flagellomere longer than second, shorter than third.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,361,1720]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Pronotum trapezoid, nearly as broad as head; sides weakly rounded with obtusely angulate or broadly rounded apical corner and short acute hind angles; hind angles short and acute; disk gently convex. Prosternum without transverse excavation between procoxae and anterior margin; procoxal cavities widely opened posteriorly; prosternal process very narrow with slightly dilated apex. Mesosternal process gradually declivous anteriorly in lateral view. Mesocoxal cavity open to episternum.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,361,1720]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Elytra elongate, more than 3 times as long as humeral width, more than 2.5 times as long as head and pronotum combined; slightly narrowed apically in male, subparallel sided in female, then roundly narrowed to apices; disk metallic green or blue. Abdomen completely covered by elytra; abdominal ventrites I about 1.5 times as long as II to V respectively. Legs moderately long and slender; femora weakly clavate; hind tarsi with first tarsomere slightly longer than the following two tarsomeres combined.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="146" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,361,1720]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1046,1072]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the combination of Latin ūnicornis, meaning one-horned and leptura, the name of the 
<typeStatus box="[1388,1436,1046,1072]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">type</typeStatus>
genus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[254,362,1082,1108]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Lepturini">Lepturini</taxonomicName>
. Gender feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,622,1117,1144]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,361,1720]" box="[199,622,1117,1144]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1117,1143]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[359,430,1118,1144]" name="China" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">China</collectingCountry>
: 
<collectingRegion box="[441,535,1118,1144]" country="China" name="Sichuan" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Sichuan</collectingRegion>
; 
<collectingRegion box="[546,618,1118,1144]" country="China" name="Hubei" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Hubei</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="146" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,361,1720]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1154,1180]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Remarks</emphasis>
. This new genus should be placed into 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[783,887,1154,1180]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Lepturini">Lepturini</taxonomicName>
by the feature of prothorax without transverse groove or depression in front of coxal cavities (
<bibRefCitation author="Gressitt, J. L." box="[672,832,1190,1217]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" refId="ref3244" refString="Gressitt, J. L. (1951) Longicorn beetles of China. In: Lepesme, P. (Ed.). Longicornia, etudes et notes sur les longicornes. Vol. 2. Paul Lechevalier, Paris, pp. 1 - 667, 22 pls." type="journal volume" year="1951">Gressitt, 1951</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Villiers, A." box="[842,996,1190,1216]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" refId="ref3440" refString="Villiers, A. (1978) Faune des Coleopteres de France, I. Cerambycidae. Encyclopedie Entomologique 42. Paul Lechevallier, Paris, xxviii + 611 pp, 1802 figs." type="book" year="1978">Villiers, 1978</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Tsherepanov, A. I." box="[1006,1219,1190,1216]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" refId="ref3400" refString="Tsherepanov, A. I. (1990) Cerambycidae of Northern Asia, volume 1. Prioninae, Disteniinae, Lepturinae, Aseminae. Oxonian Press, New Delhi, xvi + 642 pp., 296 figs." type="book" year="1990">Tsherepanov, 1990</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bense, U." box="[1229,1370,1190,1217]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" refId="ref3212" refString="Bense, U. (1995) Longicorn Beetles. Illustrated Key to the Cerambycidae and Vesperidae of Europe. Margraf Verlag, Weikersheim, 512 pp., 1260 figs." type="book" year="1995">Bense, 1995</bibRefCitation>
; etc.). It superficially resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Audinet-Serville, 1835" authorityName="Audinet-Serville" authorityYear="1835" box="[440,861,1226,1253]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Grammoptera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[440,599,1226,1252]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Grammoptera</emphasis>
Audinet-Serville, 1835
</taxonomicName>
especially the group of the subgenus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Matsushita &amp; Tamanuki" authorityYear="1940" box="[1281,1437,1226,1252]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Neoencyclops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1281,1437,1226,1252]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Neoencyclops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
regarding their overall habitus e.g. slender body, metallic colored elytra and similar proportion of body, but it can be readily distinguished from the latter by the curved scape, transverse pronotum and extremely elongate elytra. And fundamentally, it is rather unique among the Asia lepturine genera by its head significantly sexually dimorphic, provided with a cranial horn in male (
<figureCitation box="[574,654,1370,1396]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1788,1812]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,1140,1752]" captionTargetId="figure-44@4.[151,1436,1128,1764]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8–13. Head and pronotum of Unicornileptura spp. 8–11, U. emeiensis sp. nov.; 12,13, U. laticollis sp. nov. 8, 9, head in lateral view (a) and frontal view (b); 10–13, pronotum in dorsal view. 8, 10, 12, male; 9, 11, 13, female." pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Fig. 8a</figureCitation>
) which absent in female (
<figureCitation box="[943,1025,1370,1396]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1788,1812]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,1140,1752]" captionTargetId="figure-44@4.[151,1436,1128,1764]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8–13. Head and pronotum of Unicornileptura spp. 8–11, U. emeiensis sp. nov.; 12,13, U. laticollis sp. nov. 8, 9, head in lateral view (a) and frontal view (b); 10–13, pronotum in dorsal view. 8, 10, 12, male; 9, 11, 13, female." pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Fig. 9a</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,361,1720]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">
The presence of horn-shaped projection of head mostly found in male was rarely reported from worldwide 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[151,313,1442,1468]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Cerambycidae</taxonomicName>
and currently limited to some lamiine tribe which originated from different portions, e.g. single postclypeal horn in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pascoe" authorityYear="1867" box="[378,473,1479,1504]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Momisis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[378,473,1479,1504]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Momisis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of Astathini or paired in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1956" box="[764,860,1479,1504]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Mauesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[764,860,1479,1504]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Mauesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of Mauesiini; mandibular horns in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Breuning" authorityYear="1938" box="[1267,1437,1478,1504]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Chariesthoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1267,1437,1478,1504]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Chariesthoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of Tragocephalini; antennal tubercular horns in some taxon of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Svacha &amp; Lawrence, 2014)" baseAuthorityName="Svacha &amp; Lawrence" baseAuthorityYear="2014" box="[864,1313,1514,1542]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Onciderini" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
Onciderini (
<bibRefCitation author="Svacha, P. &amp; Lawrence, J. F." box="[1000,1305,1514,1542]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" pagination="1868" refId="ref3296" refString="Svacha, P. &amp; Lawrence, J. F. (2014) Vesperidae Mulsant, 1839; Oxypeltidae Lacordaire, 1868; Disteniidae J. Thomson, 1861; Cerambycidae Latreille, 1802. In: Leschen R. A. B. &amp; Beutel, R. G. (Eds.), Handbook of Zoology, Arthropoda: Insecta; Coleoptera, Beetles. Vol. 3. Morphology and systematics (Phytophaga). Walter de Gruyter, Berlin / Boston, pp. 16 - 177. https: // doi. org / 10.1515 / 9783110274462.16" type="book chapter" year="2014">Švácha &amp; Lawrence, 2014</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and also a postclypeal horn in Afirican genus 
<taxonomicName box="[552,696,1551,1576]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Prosopocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[552,696,1551,1576]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Prosopocera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Adlbauer et al., 2015)" baseAuthorityName="Adlbauer" baseAuthorityYear="2015" box="[736,1163,1550,1577]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Prosopocerini" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
Prosopocerini (
<bibRefCitation author="Adlbauer, K. &amp; Beck, R." box="[907,1156,1550,1577]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" refId="ref3175" refString="Adlbauer, K. &amp; Beck, R. (2015) Katalog und Fotoatlas der Bockkafer Athiopiens (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Taita Publishers, Hradec Kralove, 312 pp., 912 figs." type="book" year="2015">
Adlbauer 
<emphasis box="[1022,1072,1550,1576]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">et al</emphasis>
., 2015
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. The cranial specialized horn found in 
<taxonomicName authority="Bi &amp; Chen &amp; Ohbayashi, 2022" authorityName="Bi &amp; Chen &amp; Ohbayashi" authorityYear="2022" box="[312,494,1586,1612]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Unicornileptura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[312,494,1586,1612]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Unicornileptura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[502,607,1586,1612]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[502,607,1586,1612]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
probably the first discover of such structure in 
<taxonomicName box="[1142,1266,1586,1612]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Lepturinae">Lepturinae</taxonomicName>
, or even firstly reported from the whole group of longicorn beetles. Unfortunately such unique feature was recognized later in the laboratory based on dry specimens, its biological or ecological significance remains uncertain and requires further field observation.
</paragraph>
